1. c4 {Ever since I understood that nobody forced me to play only king's
fianchetto systems against 1.d4 and 1.c4, the feeling developed inside me that
my reflex answer to 1.c4 should be 1...b6. True, when reaching the board, this
idea somehow vanished, and I have played only a few games with it. The Owen
Defence is one of the most interesting and original among hyper-modern
openings. It combines ideas from several different openings, such as the
Queen's Indian, the Bogo-Indian, the Nimzo-Indian and the Dutch. Black
completely refrains from occupying the centre with his pawns and controls it
with his pieces from afar, frequently involving the f-pawn in the process.
This database aims to offer a complete Owen repertoire against 1.c4 that
avoids transpositions to the Queen's Indian or other main openings.} (1. d4 {
causes some problems if we want to play the Owen:} e6 (1... b6 2. e4 $1) 2. c4
b6 3. e4 Bb7 4. Bd3 {For a long time I held this to be problematic for Black,
but in order to offer a wider picture of this opening I have examined a viable
setup in Lines 23 and 24.}) 1... b6 2. d4 ({For} 2. Nc3 Bb7 3. e4 e5 {see
Lines 20 and 21.}) (2. Nf3 Bb7 {[%emt 0:00:22] is examined in Line 22.}) 2...
Bb7 3. Bg5 {Trying to prevent ...e7-e6 followed by ...Bb4(+). There are
several ways White can try to build up a strong centre without allowing the
pinning of the c3-knight, but they all look a bit premature.} (3. f3 {This
attempt to build up a strong centre contradicts the developing rules and can
be energetically met with} e5 $1 4. dxe5 {The critical move.} (4. e4 {wastes
too much time.} exd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd1 Bc5 7. Nc3 {Yanjinlkham,B (1951)
-Sihite,C (2227) Ulaanbaatar 2019 (1-0, 47)} f5 $1 8. exf5 Qh4+ 9. g3 Qe7+ 10.
Qe2 Nd4 11. Qxe7+ Nxe7 12. Bd3 O-O $17) (4. d5 {is strategically correct but
loses a pawn.} Qh4+ 5. g3 Qxc4 $15) (4. e3 {does not solve White's developing
problems.} exd4 5. exd4 Bd6 6. Nh3 Nc6 7. Nf2 Qh4 8. d5 Nd4 9. Nc3 O-O-O 10.
Bd3 f5 $132) 4... Nc6 $5 ({More ambitious than the also sufficient} 4... Qh4+
5. g3 Qxc4 6. e4 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Qd4 $11 {Bjelobrk,I (2112)-Garbett,P (2360)
Auckland 1999 (0-1, 32)}) 5. e4 (5. f4 f6 6. exf6 Bb4+ 7. Nc3 Nxf6 $15 {
leaves White with horrendous weaknesses on the light squares. It looks better
than the wildest Budapest Gambit dream.}) 5... Nxe5 6. Nc3 f5 7. exf5 Qh4+ 8.
g3 Qe7 $15) (3. d5 e6 4. e4 {is too straightforward to pose problems to Black.}
(4. a3 f5 5. Nc3 {transposes to Lines 2-6.}) 4... Bb4+ 5. Bd2 (5. Nd2 Nf6 6.
Bd3 exd5 7. cxd5 Qe7 {causes White problems defending his centre.}) (5. Nc3 {
transposes to Line 7.}) 5... Qe7 6. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 7. Qd2 Qxd2+ 8. Nxd2 f5 {
At this stage it is clear that Black has good counterplay.} 9. f3 Ne7 10. Ne2
O-O 11. Nc3 fxe4 12. fxe4 Ng6 13. Nf3 c6 $11 14. d6 $6 c5 $15 {[%csl Ge5][%cal
Gb8c6] , followed by ...Nc6 and the occupation of the e5-square.}) (3. Nd2 {
is too passive to be effective.} f5 $5 $146 (3... e6 4. e4 Bb4 {transposes to
a system reached after 1.d4 e6 that is supposed to be fine for Black, but we
do not need to get there, as the indicated move order is simpler.}) 4. d5 $6
Nf6 5. g3 (5. Ngf3 e6 6. dxe6 dxe6 7. g3 e5 $15 {, with freer development.})
5... c6 6. Bg2 cxd5 7. Nh3 e5 $15 {White's knights are rather poorly placed.})
(3. Qc2 {such an early queen development can hardly cause problems.} e6 4. e4
Qh4 {If} 5. Nd2 (5. Bd3 f5 6. g3 Qh5 7. Be2 Qf7 {leaves White with certain
developing problems.}) (5. Nc3 Bb4 {transposes to a position examined in Line
8.}) 5... f5 $1 {Black does not even have to play ...Bb4 but can start his
pawn counterplay at once.} 6. g3 (6. exf5 $2 Nc6 7. Ngf3 Nxd4 $1) 6... Bxe4 $1
7. Qd1 Qf6 8. Nxe4 fxe4 9. Bg2 Bb4+ 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 Nc6 12. Bxe4 d5 13.
cxd5 exd5 14. Bxd5 O-O-O {, with a strong initiative.}) (3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bb4+
5. Nd2 f5 6. Ngf3 Nf6 7. Be2 O-O 8. h3 d6 9. O-O Bxd2 10. Qxd2 a5 {leads to a
comfortable Bogo-Dutch hybrid.}) (3. Nc3 {is the mainline, of course.} e6 4. e4
({For} 4. a3 f5 {see Lines 2-6.}) 4... Bb4 {is examined in Lines 7-13.}) 3...
f6 $1 {The simplest way to enable ...e7-e6.} 4. Bh4 (4. Bf4 f5 {transposes
above.}) (4. Bd2 {is a bit passive.} e6 5. Nc3 (5. Nf3 f5 6. g3 Nf6 7. Bg2 g6
8. Nc3 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. d5 Na6 11. Bf4 Nc5 12. Nb5 d6 13. dxe6 Nfe4 14. Qc2
Nxe6 $15 {Hoelzl,F (2415)-Miles,A (2545) Baden 1980 (0-1, 40)}) 5... f5 6. Nf3
Nf6 7. g3 Nc6 8. e3 Bb4 9. Bg2 {Smejkal, J (2555)-Miles,A (2545) Baden 1980 
(1-0, 51)} Ne7 10. O-O O-O 11. a3 Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Qe8 $11 {Black has good
control on the light squares and some kingside attacking chances.}) 4... Nh6 $5
{Starting the fight against the daring bishop.} 5. e3 (5. Qc2 e6 6. f3 c5 7. e3
Nc6 8. Qd2 $2 (8. Ne2 cxd4 $11 9. exd4 $2 Rc8 $17) 8... cxd4 9. exd4 Nxd4 10.
Qxd4 Nf5 11. Qg4 Ne3 12. Qf4 Bc5 13. Bf2 Nc2+ 14. Kd1 Nxa1 15. Bxc5 bxc5 16.
Nc3 O-O 17. Kc1 d5 $17 {Miles,A (2584)-Damaso,R (2386) Lisbon 2000 (1/2-1/2,
51)}) 5... Nf5 6. Bg3 e6 7. Nf3 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 {Cox,J (2378)-Speelman,J (2525)
England 2010 (1/2-1/2, 41)} h5 9. Bd3 g5 10. e4 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 h4 $15 *

