{[%evp 0,32,21,-16,27,26,30,30,27,27,27,22,24,19,20,32,13,0,7,14,14,-31,4,-34,
-33,-16,-28,-28,-64,-65,-48,-61,-43,-41,-3]} 1. c4 b6 2. d4 Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 4. a3
{This is one of the most typical reactions to the Owen setup. The idea is
similar to the Queen's Indian Petrosian system (which involves the insertion
of Nf3 and ...Nf6 in our current line). White prevents one of Black's typical
ideas, ...Bb4, thus preparing to restrict the bishop on b7 with d4-d5 and/or
e2-e4.} f5 {If Black intends to keep the game outside the main theoretical
paths and stay within hyper-modern territory, this is the best way to do it.} (
4... Nf6 {is also good objectively, as after} 5. d5 ({The only practical
problem is that White can transpose to a genuine Queen's Indian with} 5. Nf3 {
This is not the end of the World, of course, but if I recommended this line, I
had to recommend studying a different theoretical article, too).}) 5... exd5 6.
cxd5 Bd6 {, followed by ...0-0 and .. .c7-c6.}) 5. Nf3 {In this and the next
line we examine situations in which White refrains from an early d4-d5. This
leads to a Dutch/Queen's Indian hybrid, where Black has good control over e4,
without the need to play ...Ne4 too soon. White will try to prove that ...
f7-f5 has delayed Black's development a bit and also weakened the square e6.} (
5. Nh3 {is a flexible way of developing, denying Black control over e4.} Nf6 6.
f3 (6. e3 g6 7. f3 {basically transposes.}) 6... Nc6 7. e3 (7. d5 Ne5 {offers
Black active piece play.}) 7... g6 $5 {This is the first time we see the
double-fianchetto setup. This plan is sound if White has spent a tempo on
preventing ...Bb4 and there is no immediate danger of d4-d5. In other words,
it works if Black can be sure that he will complete his development properly.}
8. Be2 (8. d5 {is once again premature:} Ne5 9. Be2 Bg7 10. O-O O-O $11 {
Black is very flexible and can continue regrouping with ...Qe7, ...Nf7,
followed by either ...e6-e5 or ... c7-c6, according to circumstances.}) 8...
Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. b4 Qe7 11. Re1 (11. Nf2 f4 $5 12. Re1 Nh5 13. b5 Na5 14. Ra2
Rac8 15. Na4 c6 $15 {Ostenstad,B (2462)-Bauer,C (2622) Plovdiv 2010 (0-1, 33)})
11... Nd8 $1 {A different way to transfer the knight to f7 after White chose
not to allow ...Ne5. Remarkably, this original plan has been played a few
times by none other than Wilhelm Steinitz!} 12. Bb2 Nf7 13. Bf1 c5 {Black
extends his control of the centre.} 14. bxc5 bxc5 15. Rb1 d6 16. dxc5 dxc5 17.
Ba1 Bc6 18. Nf2 Rad8 {The position is statically balanced. With his next moves
Black tries to take over the initiative, but play will remain equal.} 19. Qc2
Ng5 20. Be2 e5 21. Rbd1 e4 22. f4 Ne6 $11 {Portisch,L (2655)-Miles,A (2545)
Valetta 1980 (1-0, 42)}) ({The plan based on getting the same central
structure but with a different piece display initiated by} 5. e3 Nf6 6. f3 g6
7. Bd3 Bg7 8. Nge2 {is less flexible. Black's simplest answer is} c5 {followed
by ...Nc6, taking measures against e3-e4.}) ({The principled} 5. d5 {is
examined in Lines 4, 5 and 6.}) 5... Nf6 6. Bf4 {An optically appealing move,
putting pressure on the h2-b8 diagonal. But in the long run the bishop may be
exposed and even turn passive on this square and diagonal.} (6. Bg5 {is likely
to lead to simplifications:} Be7 7. e3 O-O 8. Be2 d6 9. O-O Nbd7 10. b4 Ne4 $11
) (6. e3 {can be once again met with} g6 7. Be2 (7. Bd3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. b4 d6
10. Bb2 c5 $5 $11) 7... Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. b4 Qe7 10. Rb1 Nc6 11. d5 Nd8 12. Qb3
d6 $5 $146 {Preparing to solve the problem of the restricted bishop on b7
under optimal circumstances.} (12... Nf7 13. Rd1 c6 14. dxe6 dxe6 15. c5 $14 {
Lugovoi,A (2490)-Eliet,N (2345) Antwerp 1995 (1-0, 42)}) 13. Bb2 (13. dxe6 Nxe6
14. Nd5 Qf7 15. Bb2 Rae8 {Black has a very harmonious version of the Leningrad
Dutch. If} 16. Rfd1 $6 f4 $15 {he has a dangerous initiative.}) 13... c5 {
Threatening to reach a comfortable version of the King's Indian or the Benoni
with ...e6-e5 or ... exd5, respectively.} 14. dxc6 (14. dxe6 Nxe6 15. Nd5 Qf7
16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Rfd1 Bg7 {[%cal Gf5f4,Gg6g5] , followed by the advance of
the kingside pawns, with active play.}) 14... Bxc6 15. Nd4 Bd7 16. Rfd1 Nf7 $11
{Black is perfectly regrouped and ready to start the advance of his kingside
pawns.}) (6. d5 Na6 7. g3 {transposes to Line 5.}) (6. g3 {is examined in Line
3.}) 6... Be7 7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3 {At this point it is not easy to decide how to
continue developing, as each move has a minor drawback. The last move weakens
the defence of d4.} (8. h3 {keeps the bishop safe from ...Nh5 but wastes a
tempo.} Ne4 9. Nxe4 (9. Qc2 Nxc3 10. Qxc3 Bf6 11. Be2 d6 12. Qb3 Nd7 13. c5 Bd5
14. Bc4 Bxc4 15. Qxc4 bxc5 16. Qxe6+ Kh8 17. O-O {Chernikov,O (2420)
-Grinkevich,S (2268) Tula 2004 (1-0, 52)} Qe8 $5 $11) 9... fxe4 10. Nd2 d5 11.
Be2 Rxf4 $5 12. exf4 Nc6 13. Nb3 a5 14. a4 Bb4+ 15. Kf1 Qf6 16. g3 Ne7 {
, with great compensation for the exchange due to the weaknesses on d4 and b4
and the insecure position of the white king.}) (8. Be2 {keeps d4 well defended
but is more passive.} d6 (8... Nh5 {leads to similar play as in a line below,
but with an important extra tempo for White.} 9. O-O Nxf4 10. exf4 Bf6 11. Re1
c5 12. d5 Na6 13. Ne5 d6 14. Nc6 Qd7 15. Bf3 $16) 9. O-O Ne4 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11.
h3 Nd7 12. b4 Bf6 13. Qd2 Qe8 14. Rfd1 e5 15. Bh2 {Wildes,J (1711)-Simutanyi,K
(1810) Melbourne 2010 (0-1, 32)} Qg6 {, with normal counterplay.}) 8... Nh5 9.
Bg3 ({With the bishop on d3,} 9. O-O Nxf4 10. exf4 Bf6 {forces White to spend
a tempo on} 11. Be2 c5 $11 12. d5 Na6 13. Ne5 d6 14. Nc6 Qd7 15. Bf3 e5 $15 {
We can feel that the missing Re1 with respect to a line above makes a big
difference.}) 9... d6 10. Nd2 Qe8 11. f3 Nxg3 12. hxg3 {Kazantzidis,P (1925)
-Dalaklis,G (2105) Greece 2002 (0-1, 45)} c5 13. g4 cxd4 14. exd4 Bf6 15. Nb3
g6 16. Qe2 a5 {With excellent counterplay.} *

