1. c4 b6 2. d4 Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 4. a3 f5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. g3 {This is likely to
transpose to a fianchetto Queen's Indian, where a2-a3 is not very constructive.
} Ne4 {The typical reaction in the fianchetto Queen's Indian.} 7. Qc2 {One of
the two typical reactions to the knight jump in the main Queen's Indian lines.}
(7. Nxe4 Bxe4 8. Bh3 $5 {Trying to leave the bishop on e4 exposed.} Be7 9. O-O
O-O 10. d5 Qe8 $1 {Now that the e4-bishop is in some danger, Black has to
hurry to threaten ...Qh5.} 11. Nd4 Qh5 12. Bg2 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Qf7 14. Nf3 Bf6
15. Rb1 e5 16. e4 f4 17. Ne1 Qg6 18. Qe2 d6 $11 {Georgiev,V (2576)
-Chatalbashev,B (2602) Anzere 2011 (1/2-1/2, 32)}) (7. Bg2 Nxc3 8. bxc3 {
leaves White with a weakness on c4.} Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. a4 {Shinkevich,V (2437)
-Kobo,O (2510) St Petersburg 2018 (1-0, 51)} (10. d5 Na6 11. a4 Nc5 12. a5 Bd6
13. Nd4 e5 14. Nb5 Ba6 $11 {With perfect stability for Black.}) 10... Nc6 11.
Nd2 Na5 12. e4 Qe8 $5 $15 {Due to the weakness of c4, White cannot really
enjoy his space advantage. Black can continue with ...f5-f4 or ...c7-c5,
depending on White's reactions.}) ({In the Queen's Indian,} 7. Bd2 {is the
second typical reaction.} Be7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Bf6 10. Rc1 (10. Qc2 Nxc3 11.
Bxc3 Be4 12. Qd2 d5 $5 {Deviating from the typical ...d7-d6 or ...Nc6.} 13. b3
Nc6 14. Rfd1 Qe8 15. cxd5 Bxd5 16. b4 Rd8 17. Qb2 a6 18. a4 Ne7 19. Rd2 Nc8 20.
Ne1 Nd6 $15 {With excellent play on the light squares. Schubert,T (2305)
-Kalinitschew,S (2505) Germany 1999 (0-1, 39)}) 10... c5 (10... Nc6 11. Be1 Ne7
12. b4 a6 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Bc3 b5 {This pawn break may already be familiar to
the reader from my 4.Nbd2 Bogo-Indian database. Black stabilizes on the light
squares.} 15. Nd2 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Qe8 17. e3 Qg6 $11 {Charnushevich,A (2485)
-Bauer,C (2582) Clichy 2003 (1/2-1/2, 47)}) 11. d5 (11. dxc5 bxc5 $11) 11...
exd5 12. cxd5 d6 13. h4 h6 14. Bf4 g5 15. hxg5 hxg5 16. Be3 {Tomashevsky,E 
(2706)-Morozevich,A (2739) Tromsoe 2013 (1/2-1/2, 44)} Bxc3 17. bxc3 Qe7 $15)
7... Be7 8. Bg2 Nxc3 $1 ({One of the reasons why I recommend clearing up
matters in the centre as soon as possible is that maintaining the tension (or
delaying ...Ne4) could lead to some problems:} 8... O-O 9. Ne5 $14) 9. Qxc3 Bf6
10. O-O O-O {This could be reached via the Queen's Indian move order, but in
the respective line White rarely plays a2-a3 so early.} 11. Rd1 (11. b4 c5 (
11... d6 {is also possible.} 12. Bb2 Qe7 13. Rad1 Nd7 14. Qd2 {Threatening to
lock the bishop on b7 with d4-d5.} Be4 15. Ne1 Bxg2 16. Nxg2 a5 $11) 12. Be3
Bxf3 $146 13. Bxf3 Nc6 14. Bxc6 dxc6 15. Rad1 f4 16. gxf4 Qd6 17. Qd2 cxd4 18.
Bxd4 Bxd4 19. Qxd4 Qxf4 $11) (11. Be3 d6 12. Rfd1 Qe7 13. h4 Nd7 14. Qc2 Be4
15. Qa4 e5 $15 {Miladinovic, I (2480)-Mariano,N (2345) Matinhos 1994 (1/2-1/2,
24)}) (11. Bf4 d6 12. Qd2 h6 13. h4 Qe7 14. Rad1 Nd7 15. Qc1 Be4 16. Bd2 a5 17.
Bc3 (17. b3 e5 $15) 17... a4 {As we know from the Bogo-Indian lines based on
a2-a3, Black has no reason to refrain from freezing the queenside.} 18. Ne1 e5
19. Bxe4 fxe4 20. Ng2 exd4 21. Bxd4 {Urosevic,A (2281)-Zaja,I (2497) Bosnjaci
2011 (1/2-1/2, 53)} Bxd4 22. Rxd4 Nc5 $15) 11... Qe7 12. b3 (12. b4 d6 13. Bb2
Nd7 14. Qb3 a5 15. Rac1 (15. d5 Bxb2 16. Qxb2 e5 $11 {, followed by ...Nf6.})
15... axb4 16. axb4 b5 $1 {Once again this typical Bogo-Indian idea.} 17. Nd2 (
17. cxb5 Nb6 18. Ne1 Bd5 19. Bxd5 Nxd5 20. Nc2 Rab8 21. Ne3 Rxb5 22. Nxd5 exd5
$11) 17... Bxg2 18. Kxg2 bxc4 (18... Nb6 19. cxb5 Nd5 $11) 19. Nxc4 Rfb8 20.
Ne3 d5 21. Rxc7 Qd6 (21... Qxb4 $2 22. Rc8+ $1 {Cebalo,M (2535)-Lovric,B (2335)
Porec 1998 (1-0, 33)}) 22. Qc3 Bd8 23. Rc6 Qxb4 $11) 12... c5 (12... Nc6 $5 13.
Bb2 Nd8 {, followed by ...Nf7 and ...g7-g5 pursues the hyper-modern spirit.})
13. Bb2 Nc6 14. Qc2 d6 15. d5 (15. e3 Nd8 $11 {[%cal Gd8f7]}) 15... exd5 16.
Rxd5 (16. cxd5 Ne5 $11) 16... Na5 17. Ne1 f4 18. Rad1 Rad8 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 20.
Nd3 fxg3 21. hxg3 Nc6 $13 {With excellent Black counterplay, compensating for
the weakness on d5. Brunello,S (2562)-Moroni,L (2460) Milan 2015 (0-1, 76)} *

