1. c4 b6 2. d4 Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 4. a3 f5 5. d5 {This is the most principled way
of justifying a2-a3. Since he does not have ...Bb4, Black will face problems
undermining d5. The best idea is to use the c5-square for his queen's knight's
trajectory.} Nf6 6. Nf3 (6. dxe6 {is an obvious concession. White exchanges
the pawn into which he had already invested two tempi, clearing the
b7-bishop's path at the same time.} dxe6 (6... Bd6 $5 7. exd7+ Nbxd7 {is also
interesting. For the pawn, Black has a considerable advance in development.})
7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 (8. Nf3 Bd6 9. Nb5 Nbd7 $11) 8... Bd6 9. Bxd6 cxd6 10. Nb5
Ne8 11. Rd1 Ke7 12. e3 Nd7 13. Nf3 a6 14. Nc3 Nef6 {Black has almost completed
his development and the king is well placed on e7.} 15. Be2 Rac8 16. Nd2 Ne5
17. f3 g5 18. Kf2 h5 19. h4 g4 $15 {Djoric,D (2288)-Zaja,I (2477) Hum na Sutli
2015 (0-1, 32)}) (6. Nh3 Na6 7. g3 {[%emt 0:00:06] transposes to Line 6.}) (6.
g3 {is examined in Lines 5 and 6.}) 6... Na6 {At this point the most flexible
move. There is no other way of developing the knight, while the bishop on f8
may have a choice soon.} 7. Bf4 (7. g3 Nc5 {[%emt 0:00:05] transposes to Line
5.}) (7. b4 {implies consuming some time and weakening the long diagonal.
These are enough to justify switching to Steinitz' old plan, which is familiar
to us already.} g6 8. Bb2 Bg7 9. Qb3 (9. g3 exd5 10. Nxd5 O-O 11. Bg2 (11. Qb3
c5 12. Bg2 Nxd5 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. cxd5 Qe7 $11) 11... Nxd5 12. Bxg7 Ne3 $1 13.
fxe3 Kxg7 14. Qd4+ Qf6 $5 15. Qxd7+ Rf7 16. Qd4 c5 17. Qxf6+ Kxf6 18. b5 Nc7
19. Kf2 Rd8 20. Rhd1 Rfd7 21. Rxd7 Rxd7 22. a4 Ne8 {[%cal Ge8d6] , followed by
...Nd6. White's extra pawn is not relevant and rather counts as a weakness.})
9... O-O 10. e3 Qe7 $1 $146 {The best way to prepare ...c7-c5.} (10... c5 {
is a bit premature.} 11. dxc6 {In Suba,M (2512)-Bauer,C (2625) Calvia 2005 
(1-0, 50), the principled move was} dxc6 {, preparing to activate the knight
and bishop with ...c6-c5, but White could answer} 12. c5 $14) 11. Be2 c5 12.
dxc6 dxc6 {With e6 defended, Black is safe against c4-c5.} 13. O-O c5 14. b5
Nb8 15. a4 a5 16. Nd2 (16. Ne5 Nfd7 17. Nd3 Ne5 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. Rad1 Nd7 $11)
16... Nbd7 17. f4 Rad8 $11 {With comfortable black play in both cases.}) (7.
Bg5 Be7 {exposes the bishop to the permanent threat ...Nxd5.} 8. e3 Nc5 9. Nd4
a5 10. Be2 O-O 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. O-O a4 $15 {Morovic Fernandez,I (2608)-Bauer,
C (2562) Saint Vincent 2000 (1/2-1/2, 33)}) 7... g6 {Once again, the most
active way to develop the bishop.} 8. g3 (8. e3 {puts less pressure on the
centre.} Bg7 9. dxe6 (9. b4 O-O 10. Rc1 {Dreev,A (2658)-Grabuzova,T (2357)
Moscow 2007 (1-0, 30)} c5 11. dxc6 dxc6 12. Bd6 Re8 13. c5 {Otherwise Black
would free his position with ... c6-c5.} bxc5 14. bxc5 Nd7 15. Nb1 Bf8 $15 {
Being underdeveloped, White cannot maintain his domination.}) 9... dxe6 10.
Qxd8+ Rxd8 11. Be5 O-O 12. Nd4 Rfe8 13. f3 Nd7 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. O-O-O c6 16.
Be2 e5 17. Nc2 Ndc5 18. b4 Ne6 19. Kb2 Nac7 20. Na1 c5 $11 {, with a perfect
