1. c4 b6 2. d4 Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 4. a3 f5 5. d5 Nf6 6. g3 {This is the approved
and most consistent way to strengthen control of the centre after d4-d5.} Na6 {
In this setup the bishop usually goes to d6 and often later to e5, in order to
undermine White's defence of d5. But once again I believe that developing and
activating the knight are higher priorities for Black at this point.} (6... Bd6
7. Bg2 O-O 8. Nh3 Na6 9. Nb5 {is a bit unpleasant for Black.}) 7. Bg2 ({
With the pawn on d5 vulnerable and pinned,} 7. b4 {fails to maintain White's
queenside control.} c5 8. dxc6 (8. b5 Nc7 9. Bg2 Bd6 10. f4 {1/2-1/2 Serper,G 
(2558)-Kraai,J (2445) Los Angeles 2001} exd5 11. Nh3 a6 12. bxa6 Rxa6 $17) 8...
dxc6 9. Bg2 (9. Qxd8+ Rxd8 10. Bg2 e5 $11 11. b5 $6 Nb8 12. Bb2 Bc5 13. e3 O-O
14. Na4 Bd6 $15 {Black is better developed and already threatens ...cxb5.})
9... Qxd1+ 10. Nxd1 (10. Kxd1 {Lazarev,V (2445)-Lempert,I (2495) Bled 1994 
(0-1, 40)} e5 $11) 10... Nb8 11. Nh3 (11. b5 a6 12. Bb2 axb5 13. cxb5 Ne4 14.
bxc6 Nxc6 15. Nf3 Rg8 16. O-O g5 $11) 11... Bd6 12. b5 (12. O-O Nbd7 $11) 12...
Ke7 13. O-O Rc8 {, followed by ...Nbd7. Black has normal play in all these
lines.}) 7... Nc5 {Black continues the knight manoeuvre, maintaining all the
options regarding his bishop.} (7... g6 {may be playable in principle, but
this slow approach allows Black to maintain control of the centre.} 8. Nh3 Bg7
9. O-O O-O 10. Rb1 $5 {followed by b2-b4 soon offers White chances to maintain
control..}) 8. Nf3 {This natural developing move allows Black to display one
of his main ideas connected with the early knight manoeuvre.} (8. Qc2 {is a
half-waiting move, over-defending e4 and forcing Black to commit his bishop.}
Bd6 9. Nf3 (9. Nb5 exd5 {This is another moment that reveals the usefulness of
the knight manoeuvre, as the bishop on b7 is defended and the threat of ...
dxc4 real.} 10. Nxd6+ cxd6 11. b4 (11. Qxf5 {Pardoe,I (1484)-Forjan Jimenez,P
