1. c4 b6 2. d4 Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 {We have been examining this move order for a
while by now, but I think this is the right moment to explain it.} (3... f5 {
would prevent 4.e4, which is the core of the next lines, but allow} 4. Bg5 $5
h6 (4... Nf6 5. Bxf6 $1 {spoils Black's structure in an unpleasant way.}) 5.
Bh4 g5 6. e3 Nf6 7. Bg3 $14 {Black's Dutch hybrid is less flexible than usual,
as he has weakened his kingside.}) 4. e4 {This is a very active approach.
White picks up the gauntlet and gets all the space he can.} Bb4 {An important
element of Black's play. It is important to use all the minor pieces when
fighting against White's centre. In many lines, he can build up his
counterplay against the queenside weaknesses resulting from the exchange on c3.
