{Too straightforward to be dangerous.} (5. Qg4 {This early queen incursion is
likely to hand over the initiative to Black.} Nf6 $1 6. Qxg7 Rg8 7. Qh6 Rg6 8.
Qe3 (8. Qh3 Nxe4 9. Nge2 Qf6 10. f3 c5 $1 $146 11. fxe4 cxd4 $15 12. a3 $2 dxc3
13. axb4 cxb2 $19) 8... Nxe4 9. a3 (9. Nf3 c5 $15) 9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Nd6 11.
Nh3 Nf5 12. Qd3 d6 (12... Nc6 $5 13. Nf4 Rg8 14. Be2 Na5 {[%cal Ga5b3] ,
planning either ...Ba6 or ...Nb3.}) 13. Nf4 Rg8 14. d5 $6 (14. Be2 {is safer,
even though Black has good play anyway.} Nd7 15. O-O Qf6 $132) 14... Qf6 15. g3
Na6 $15 {Bondarev,B (1986)-Koshelev,A Krasnodar 2012 (1/2-1/2, 58)}) (5. Qe2 {
is worse than 5.Qc2, as after} Qh4 {White cannot defend the pawn with Bd3
anymore.}) (5. e5 {offers Black a clear plan to proceed with his development
and undermine the white centre:} Ne7 6. Nf3 c5 7. a3 (7. dxc5 Bxf3 $5 8. Qxf3
Nbc6 9. cxb6 axb6 10. Qe4 Ra5 11. f4 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 g5 13. g3 gxf4 14. gxf4 Nf5
{Black's better structure and stable knights offer him ample compensation for
the pawn.}) 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 d6) (5. Qc2 {is examined in Line 8.}) (5. Bd3 {
is the subject of Lines 9 and 10.}) ({For} 5. f3 {see Lines 11, 12 and 13.})
5... Qe7 {A flexible move, creating a potential pin along the e-file.} 6. Be2 (
6. Be3 {delays the kingside development, justifying radical measures:} f5 7.
exf5 exd5 8. cxd5 Nf6 {White loses ground in the centre.} 9. Nh3 (9. a3 Bxc3+
10. bxc3 Nxd5 11. Qh5+ Kd8 12. Kd2 Nxe3 13. fxe3 Re8 14. Qh3 Na6 $19 {
Lehtosaari,K-Kauppila,O (2200) Kokkola 2002 (0-1, 29)}) (9. Bc4 Qe4 10. Be2
