problem, of course, but Black can opt for a hybrid, combining the Dutch with
both of these openings! This way, he can stay within Owen territory.} f5 5. Bg5
{Developing the bishop at such an early stage mainly exposes it.} ({This also
applies to} 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 Bb4 7. Bd3 (7. Qb3 Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 O-O 9. Be2 d6 10.
O-O Ne4 11. Qc2 g5 12. Bg3 h5 {, with an initiative.}) 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 O-O
9. O-O d6 10. Nd2 (10. h3 Nbd7 11. Bh2 Qe7 12. Nd2 g6 13. Re1 e5 $11 14. e4 $6
f4 $15 {Tretyakov,S (1967)-Ponfilenok,V (2395) Kazan 2016 (0-1, 34)}) 10...
Nbd7 11. Bg3 Qe8 12. f3 Nh5 13. Bf2 {Suleymanli,A (2210)-Haria,R (2424) Batumi
2018 (0-1, 28)} e5 $11) (5. d5 Nf6 6. g3 ({The sounder} 6. a3 {[%emt 0:00:06]
transposes to Line 6.}) 6... Bb4 7. Bd2 O-O 8. Bg2 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 exd5 10. Nh4
Ne4 11. Qd4 Nxc3 12. Qxc3 Qf6 13. Qd2 Na6 14. cxd5 Nc5 15. Rd1 Rae8 16. O-O a5
17. Nf3 f4 $15 {, with active play. Zilberstein,D (2379)-Yermolinsky,A (2568)
San Diego 2004 (1/2-1/2, 25)}) (5. a3 {transposes to Line 2 or 3.}) (5. e3 {
[%emt 0:00:16] is examined in Lines 15 and 16.}) (5. g3 {is the subject of
Lines 17 and 18.}) 5... Nf6 {I like the idea of maintaining the possibility of
...Bb4.} (5... Be7 {is popular and entirely justified if White plays} 6. Bxe7 (
{I would be a bit worried of} 6. h4 {, though.}) 6... Qxe7 7. e3 Nf6 8. Bd3 O-O
