1. c4 b6 2. d4 Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 4. Nf3 f5 5. e3 Nf6 6. Bd3 Bb4 7. O-O {This is a
dynamic approach. White does not waste time with Bd2, hoping that his massive
centre will offer him chances to take over the initiative.} Bxc3 8. bxc3 O-O 9.
Ba3 {One of the possible plans.} ({In the Nimzo-Indian, the most popular idea
is to put the centre in motion, starting with a knight retreat and followed by
f2-f3 and e3-e4. Since in our Nimzo-Dutch hybrid the black knight is on f6,
this plan does not gain time for White anymore. This offers Black the
possibility of blocking the threatening centre.} 9. Ne1 c5 10. f3 Nc6 (10...
Qe7 11. Nc2 d6 12. Qe2 Nc6 13. e4 {Hernandez Onna,R (2435)-Piasetski,L (2395)
Alicante 1977 (1/2-1/2, 57)} fxe4 14. fxe4 Nd7 15. Be3 Rxf1+ 16. Rxf1 Rf8 $11)
11. Bb2 Qe7 12. Qe2 d6 13. g3 Rae8 14. Ng2 g6 15. Qd2 Na5 16. Rae1 Qc7 17. Qe2
e5 18. e4 exd4 19. cxd4 cxd4 20. Bxd4 Nc6 21. Bxf6 Rxf6 22. Qb2 Ne5 23. exf5 {
Sreeshwan,M (2244)-Marin,M (2539) Roquetas de Mar 2019 (1/2-1/2, 61)} Rff8 $15)
(9. Nd2 d6 10. f3 c5 11. Qe2 (11. e4 fxe4 12. fxe4 Nc6 13. Nf3 e5 14. d5 Ne7
$11 {[%cal Gb7c8]}) 11... Nc6 $11 {Nakauchi,G (2191)-Cheng,B (2377) Cammeray
2013 (0-1, 53)}) ({Another plan is to attack the b6-pawn, trying to shake
Black's queenside stability.} 9. a4 Nc6 10. Ba3 (10. Nd2 d6 11. Nb3 Ne7 12. a5
c5 $11 {Rubinstein,A-Maroczy,G Teplitz Schoenau 1922 (1-0, 33) White has spent
too much time on his plan and the knight stands badly on b3. Black does not
have any special problems.}) 10... d6 (10... Re8 11. Nd2 d6) 11. d5 exd5 (11...
Na5 12. Ng5) 12. cxd5 Ne7 13. c4 $16 {Dmitrienko,A (2216)-Lysyj,I (2490) Tomsk
2003 (35, 0-1)}) (9. c5 Ne4 10. cxb6 axb6 11. c4 d6 (11... Nc3 12. Qe1 Bxf3 13.
gxf3 Qg5+ 14. Kh1 Qh5 15. Rg1 Qxf3+ 16. Rg2 Rf6 17. Kg1 Ne4 18. Be2 Qh3 19. f3
Nd6 20. c5 Ne8 21. cxb6 cxb6 22. d5 $13) (11... Rf6 $132 12. Nd2 Rh6 13. Nxe4
Qh4 14. h3 Bxe4 15. Bxe4 fxe4 $15 {[%cal Gb8c6]}) 12. Bb2 Nd7 13. Nd2 e5 $11
14. Bxe4 fxe4 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 dxe5 17. c5 b5 18. Nb3 (18. Qb3+ Qd5 19.
Qb2 Bc6 $11) 18... Bd5 19. Qc2 c6 $15 {0-1 (30) Anagnostopoulos,K (2117)
-Nabaty,T (2604) Anogia 2015}) 9... Re8 $5 {My favourite move, maintaining the
structural flexibility.} (9... d6 {is not a bad move, but it exposes Black to
two different pawn breaks.} 10. d5 {The thematical pawn break after ...d7-d6,
but with the bishop relatively passive on a3, the consequences are not that
clear. It was better to keep the tension with:} ({The alternative was} 10. c5 {
, when Black could hold approximate equality with} dxc5 11. dxc5 Re8 {[%cal
Gb8d7] For instance:} 12. Bb5 Bc6 13. c4 Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 bxc5 15. Bxc5 a6 16.
Bxc6 Nxc6 $11) 10... Qe8 $5 $146 {, for instance:} (10... exd5 $6 {Capturing
too early on d5 unblocks the c3-pawn, helping the a3-bishop to join the fight
