1. c4 b6 2. d4 Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 4. Nf3 f5 5. g3 {As usual, the king's fianchetto
is a complex way of neutralising the b7-bishop's pressure along the long
diagonal.} Nf6 6. Bg2 Bb4 7. O-O {With the pawn on c4 not defended by the
bishop, this looks very double-edged.} (7. Qb3 {is simplest met with} Bxc3+ ({
Defending the bishop with, say,} 7... a5 {, mainly wastes a tempo, as after} 8.
O-O {Black should take on c3 anyway in view of threats like Nb5 or Na4.}) 8.
Qxc3 O-O 9. O-O Qe8 10. b4 (10. Bf4 d6 11. b4 Nbd7 $11) 10... d6 11. Bb2 (11.
a4 {Williams,S (2369)-Gleizerov,E (2587) Port Erin 2001 (0-1, 43)} a5 12. b5
Nbd7 $11 {Breaking with c4-c5 is not that simple now, and if d5-d4 or ...
e6-e5 and ...exd4 Black will get control over c5.}) 11... a5 12. a3 Be4 13. Nd2
(13. d5 e5 14. Ng5 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Ne4 16. Nxe4 fxe4 17. Qe3 Qg6 18. c5 bxc5 19.
