cannot be proud of his bishop. Moreover, d5 is weaker than e4.}) 13... Bxg2 14.
Kxg2 Nbd7 15. f3 axb4 {Sokolov,I (2670)-Timman,J (2590) Groningen 1996 (1/2-1/
2, 17)} 16. axb4 Qg6 17. Qc2 b5 $1 {A familiar idea from the 4.Nbd2
Bogo-Indian database.} 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 19. cxb5 Nd5 20. Qc6 N7b6 21. Nc4 Ra2 22.
Nxb6 cxb6 $11) (7. Qc2 {is less accurate, as it allows Black to gain a useful
tempo:} Be4 8. Qb3 a5 9. O-O Bxc3 10. Qxc3 O-O 11. b3 Qe8 12. Bb2 d6 13. a3
Nbd7 14. b4 b5 $1) (7. Bd2 {is examined in Line 18.}) 7... Bxc3 8. bxc3 O-O 9.
d5 {The most interesting continuation. White gives up the control over c5, but
tries to put pressure on the light squares, hoping to use his slightly
superior development.} (9. Ba3 Re8 10. c5 {does not challenge Black's
stability in any way. In fact, we know that in many lines Black tries to
