1. c4 b6 2. Nc3 Bb7 3. e4 {With this move order, White intends to keep the
game within English territory.} e5 $5 {Black has more than one good plan here.}
({For instance} 3... e6 4. Nge2 Nf6 (4... c5 {would soon lead to some Hedgehog
structure.}) 5. e5 Ne4 {I have chosen 3...e5 as our repertoire variation for
several reasons. It is a common choice of Nigel Short, probably the strongest
player employing the Owen regularly, it is quite original and it forces White
to play "our structure").}) 4. Nge2 {White is developing in the spirit of the
Botvinnik English setup.} (4. g3 {may lead to the same but offers Black a
choice:} f5 5. Bg2 Nf6 6. d3 (6. Nd5 $2 fxe4 7. Bxe4 {Zlatanovic,B (2428)
-Atalik,S (2599) Paracin 2012 (0-1, 40)} Bxd5 8. Bxd5 Nxd5 9. cxd5 Qf6 10. Ne2
Bc5 11. O-O O-O $17 {Atalik}) 6... fxe4 $1 (6... Bc5 $6 {is less precise, as
it allows White to fight for the initiative:} 7. Nf3 fxe4 8. Nxe5) 7. Nge2 Bc5
8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 {Consistently fighting for the light squares.} (9. Nxe4 $6 {
offers Black a great game:} Nxe4 10. dxe4 Nc6 11. Bd2 Rf7 12. Nc3 Qf8 13. Qe1
Nd4 14. Rc1 Nf3+ 15. Bxf3 Rxf3 $17 {Guichard,P (2407)-Cornette,D (2405) Monaco
2019 (1-0, 39)}) 9... h6 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Bxe4 c6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 $11 {(Atalik).
Black will soon complete his development with ...Na6 (maybe after ...a7-a5) ,
keeping good control of the dark squares.}) (4. Nf3 {is examined in Line 21.})
4... Nf6 ({Since White's development is better than after 4.g3,} 4... f5 $2 {
is refuted by} 5. d4 $1 $16) 5. d3 Bc5 {This is the main idea of 3...e5, of
course.} 6. h3 {Preventing ...Ng4.} (6. Ng3 {does the same but abandons the
plan based on g2-g3.} Nc6 $146 (6... g6 {, planning ...h7-h5, would be fine if}
7. Bh6 $146 {wasn't creating some micro problems.}) 7. Be2 Nd4 8. O-O O-O 9.
Kh1 (9. Na4 {is not threatening that much, as if} d6 10. Nxc5 dxc5 {Black will
have a perfect position in the centre. If} 11. f4 exf4 12. Bxf4 Nd7 13. Qd2 Re8
14. Rad1 Ne5 {, the blockade is perfect.}) 9... Ne6 {Taking measures against
f2-f4.} 10. Nf5 g6 11. Nh6+ Kh8 12. Nd5 Ng8 $11) ({Apart from not threatening
much, the early} 6. Na4 {allows} Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ $146 ({Simpler than} 7... a5
8. a3 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 {It may be better to stick to the same plan as in the main
line.} Nc6 10. g3 Qe7 11. Bg2 h5 {Claridge Hansen,W (2290)-Pein,J (2151)
London 2019 (1/2-1/2, 40)} 12. Nac3 $14) 8. Qxd2 c6 {Preparing ...d6-d5.} 9. f4
d6 10. Nac3 O-O 11. g3 b5 $5 12. Bg2 (12. cxb5 cxb5 13. Nxb5 Ba6 {offers Black
a strong initiative for the pawn:} 14. Nbc3 Nc6 15. Bg2 Nb4 16. Nc1 Qb6 17. a3
Nc6) 12... Qb6 13. a4 b4 14. Nd1 a5 15. Nf2 Re8 16. O-O Nbd7 17. d4 exd4 18.
Nxd4 Nc5 19. Rfe1 Rad8 $11 {With such a knight on c5, Black has little to
complain about. He might play ...d6-d5 soon.}) 6... c6 $1 {The logical way to
react to White's slow development. The threat ...d7-d5 is quite unpleasant.} 7.
Ng3 (7. g3 d5 8. Bg2 (8. exd5 cxd5 9. Bg2 Qd7 $15 {Atalik}) 8... dxc4 9. dxc4 {
Padovani,A (2107)-Luciani,V (2182) Riva del Garda 2004 (0-1, 67)} Qxd1+ 10.
Nxd1 O-O 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Ne3 Rfd8 13. b3 Nf8 $11 {With easy play for Black,
who has the d4-square to work around.}) (7. g4 d5 8. g5 Ng8 $132 {Atalik}) 7...
d5 8. Nf5 g6 9. Ng3 {This is simply a loss of time.} (9. Ng7+ $2 Ke7 $1 {
(Atalik) self-traps the knight.}) ({Atalik recommends} 9. Nh6 {, but Black has
a great game anyway. He is better developed and has the centre. For instance:}
d4 (9... dxc4 $6 {allows} 10. Qf3 $1 {, with the initiative.}) 10. Ne2 Ng8 11.
Nxg8 Bb4+ 12. Bd2 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 Rxg8 14. Qh6 Qe7 15. O-O-O (15. Qxh7 Qf8 16.
Qh4 Qb4+ $17) 15... Nd7 16. Qxh7 O-O-O 17. Qh6 f5 $15 {White's extra pawn does
not make itself felt while his delay in development and lack of space does.})
9... dxc4 $1 10. dxc4 Qxd1+ 11. Nxd1 h5 $1 $17 {With fantastic play on the
dark squares, Marjanovic,A (2325)-Atalik,S (2509) Paracin 2018 (0-1, 39).} *

