1. c4 b6 2. Nc3 Bb7 3. e4 e5 4. Nf3 {Since the slow development examined in
the previous line exposes White to underdevelopment, this move looks better.
But giving up the possibility of a quick f2-f4 implies some positional
self-limitations.} Nc6 5. d4 {The most principled continuation, but a risky
one in view of Black's 6th move.} (5. g3 {is a less aggressive setup than with
the knight on e2.} g6 $5 6. Bg2 Bg7 7. O-O Nge7 {It is now clear that Black
will advance his f-pawn sooner than White.} 8. d3 O-O 9. Nd5 d6 10. Be3 Qd7 11.
Qd2 {Krogius,N (2465)-Gurgenidze,B (2370) Bad Wildbad 1993 (1/2-1/2, 29)} f5
$11) (5. Be2 {is safe, but obviously not ambitious.} Bc5 6. Nxe5 {is the best
chance to reach a normal position.} (6. O-O {This neutral plan offers Black
easy play.} d6 7. a3 (7. Na4 Nge7 8. Nxc5 dxc5 $17 {leaves White with serious
problems along the d-file.}) 7... a5 8. d3 Nge7 9. Rb1 (9. Be3 O-O 10. Nd5 {
Carlstedt,J (2442)-Ehlvest,J (2535) Berlin 2015 (0-1, 54)} f5 $15) 9... O-O 10.
Nd5 (10. b3 f5 $15) 10... a4 $5 (10... Nxd5 11. cxd5 Nd4 $11) 11. Nc3 Nd4 12.
Nxd4 Bxd4 13. Nxa4 f5 14. exf5 (14. Bf3 Qe8 15. Nc3 Bxc3 16. bxc3 fxe4 17. Bxe4
Bxe4 18. dxe4 Ng6 $15 {White's extra pawn does not count for much while his
weaknesses do.}) 14... Rxa4 $1 15. Qxa4 Nxf5 {, with a strong attack.} 16. Bg4
(16. Kh1 Qh4 $19) 16... Nh4 $17) 6... Nxe5 7. d4 Bd6 8. dxe5 Bxe5 9. Nd5 Nf6
10. f4 Bd6 11. Nxf6+ (11. Bf3 {is more consistent and leads to original play:}
Nxd5 12. cxd5 Bc5 13. Qd3 O-O {[%cal Gc7c6]} 14. Bd2 c6 15. d6 a5 16. e5 Ba6
17. Qc2 f6 {, with good counterplay in a rather unusual position.}) 11... Qxf6
12. e5 Bb4+ 13. Bd2 Bxd2+ 14. Qxd2 Qh4+ 15. g3 Qh3 16. Bf1 Qe6 17. Bg2 Bxg2 18.
Qxg2 O-O $11 {Sullivan,D (1972)-Gill,O (2022) England 2014 (0-1, 43)}) 5...
exd4 6. Nxd4 Bb4 $1 {Black finally plays this move, typical for many Owen
lines. White will most likely get doubled pawns on the c-file.} 7. Be3 (7. Nxc6
Bxc3+ $1 8. bxc3 Bxc6 9. Qd4 (9. Bd3 {looks more natural.} Ne7 10. O-O Ng6 11.
f4 O-O $11) 9... Nf6 (9... Qf6 {mainly exposes the black queen.} 10. Bd3 Qg6
11. O-O Ne7 12. Ba3 d6 13. f3 Qg5 14. f4 Qa5 15. Bb4 Qh5 16. Rf3 {Delchev,A 
(2560)-Blatny,P (2512) Budapest 2000 (0-1, 34)} O-O-O $11) 10. Bd3 (10. Qe5+
Qe7 {mainly aggravates White's strategic problems, as without queens his space
advantage will partly lose relevance.}) (10. e5 Qe7 11. Be2 Ne4 $15) 10... Qe7
11. O-O d6 12. Ba3 O-O-O 13. Rae1 Nd7 14. f4 f6 {Black has a perfectly safe
king's position and the better structure. This will favour him in the long
term.} 15. e5 fxe5 16. fxe5 Nxe5 17. Be4 Qe8 18. Bd5 Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Kb8 20. c5
Qb5 21. c4 Nxc4 22. Rb1 Qa6 23. cxd6 Nxd6 $19 {Rydl,J (2122)-Blahynka,M (2235)
Czechia 2014 (0-1, 41)}) (7. Be2 {does not change much:} Nf6 8. f3 Bxc3+ 9.
bxc3 O-O) (7. Nde2 {is most actively met with} f5 $1 $146 8. exf5 Qf6 9. a3 (9.
g4 $2 Ne5) 9... Bxc3+ 10. Nxc3 Nd4 $36 {, with a strong initiative.}) 7...
Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nf6 9. f3 d6 10. Be2 Nd7 {In principle the position remains
complex, but Black's play is easier, as he has the square c5 and a target on
c4.} 11. O-O O-O 12. Qe1 Kh8 13. Qg3 Qf6 14. h4 Qe5 15. Qf2 Nc5 16. Nb5 $6 {
Unnecessarily weakening control of the centre.} ({But Black is doing fine
anyway, for instance} 16. Rad1 Rae8 17. Rfe1 f6 18. Bf1 Qh5 19. g4 Qf7 20. h5
Ne5) 16... Qe7 17. Rfd1 f5 $17 {Pechenkin,V (2312)-Short,N (2705) Edmonton
2012 (0-1, 26)} *

