1. c4 b6 2. Nf3 {White tries to take the game along the "quiet English" paths.
Apart from transposing to known systems like the English Hedgehog, Black can
keep the game on original paths.} Bb7 3. g3 (3. Nc3 {exposes the knight to an
exchange Black is aiming for:} e6 4. g3 Bb4 5. Bg2 (5. Qb3 Bxf3 6. exf3 Nc6 {
offers Black great play on the dark squares.}) 5... Bxc3 6. bxc3 (6. dxc3 {
is strategically inconsistent.} Nf6 7. O-O O-O 8. Bg5 d6 $11) 6... Ne7 {
The start of a flexible regrouping, anticipating White's central expansion.} 7.
O-O O-O 8. d3 (8. a4 Nbc6 9. d3 Na5 10. e4 f5 11. exf5 Nxf5 {, with excellent
play in Pigusov,E (2575)-Ehlvest,J (2625) Novosibirsk 1993 (0-1, 40)}) 8... d6
9. e4 Nd7 10. Re1 e5 11. a4 a5 12. d4 Ng6 13. Ba3 Re8 14. Qc2 Nf6 {Black has
reached a comfortable Nimzo-Indian setup, with all his minor pieces optimally
placed.} 15. Nd2 Qd7 16. f3 Ba6 17. Bf1 h6 18. Bd3 Nh7 $11 {Kasparov,G (2838)
-Kramnik,V (2802) Moscow (rapid) 2001 (1/2-1/2, 42)}) (3. e3 {deviates (at
least temporarily) from the plans based on g2-g3, allowing Black to choose the
double-fianchetto Dutch.} f5 4. b3 Nf6 5. Bb2 e6 6. g3 g5 $5 ({I had initially
placed my pawn on g6 without releasing it. But when I noticed the pin along
the long diagonal, I instantly decided that I could do better!} 6... g6 {
is entirely okay, of course.}) 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. O-O g4 9. Nh4 Bxg2 10. Kxg2 Nc6
11. f3 Qe7 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Qe2 Ne5 14. d4 Ng6 15. Nxg6 hxg6 {, with good play
on the light squares. Foisor,O (2440)-Marin,M (2545) Baile Tusnad 1997 (0-1,
36)}) 3... Bxf3 $5 {The only reasonable way to stay within Owen territory.} (
3... c5 {transposes to the English Hedgehog, the subject of an earlier
database of mine.}) (3... f5 {does not work so well now.} 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. O-O g6
6. d4 Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. d5 {White has spared the tempo a2-a3 and has chances
to maintain his domination in the centre.}) 4. exf3 c5 5. d4 {Practically
forced, as otherwise Black would retain control over d4.} (5. Bg2 Nc6 6. f4 g6
{is very comfortable, of course.}) 5... Nc6 {Playing for the d4-square.} (5...
cxd4 6. Qxd4 Nc6 {is by far more popular, but I feel that White has chances to
retain a small plus due to his free development and two bishops.}) 6. d5 {
The critical line.} (6. dxc5 bxc5 7. Bg2 g6 {doesn't pose any problems.}) 6...
Nd4 7. Be3 {The most challenging move.} (7. Bg2 {allows Black to consolidate
the knight with} g6 8. O-O Bg7 9. Re1 e6 $5 $146 {Black needs to fight for the
centre.} (9... d6 $6 {is likely to doom Black to a passive position:} 10. Nc3
Nf6 11. Ne2 Nxe2+ 12. Rxe2 a6 13. Bg5 Ra7 14. Qc2 O-O 15. Rae1 b5 16. b3 Kh8
17. h4 $14 {Aguilar,A (2252)-Dolezal,C (2395) Buenos Aires 2018 (0-1, 56)}) 10.
f4 Rc8 11. Nc3 Ne7 12. Qa4 O-O $11) 7... e5 8. dxe6 (8. Bg2 {is best answered
with} Bd6 $1 {Black aims for rapid development in order to reduce the impact
of f3-f4.} 9. O-O Nf6 10. Nc3 O-O {Black has little to fear, for instance} 11.
Ne4 Nxe4 12. fxe4 g6 $11) 8... dxe6 9. Nc3 Qd7 10. Bg2 Rd8 11. O-O g6 12. Ne4 {
Martinez,J (2076)-Grimberg,G (2341) France 2009 (0-1, 37)} Bg7 {, followed by .
..h7-h6 and ...Nge7 with comfortable play. If immediately ...Nge7, then Bg5 is
unpleasant.} 13. Re1 *

