1. d4 e6 {As promised, we will examine the possible expansion of the Owen
repertoire after 1.d4.} 2. c4 {The most active move, but one allowing us to
play the Owen.} (2. g3 {and}) (2. Nf3 {require examining other openings as
well. But this could be an effective move order if White is a player who
prefers the Nimzo-Indian to the Catalan or the Queen's Indian and the Bogo.})
2... b6 3. e4 Bb7 4. Bd3 {This is the crucial move, somewhat reducing Black's
chances for counterplay. But it seems that he can work a way out here, too.}
Bb4+ {Black clears the f8-square for his king in order to prepare ...f7-f5.} (
4... f5 $2 {leads to trouble after} 5. exf5 Bxg2 6. Qh5+ {, as Black does not
have the f8-square for his king:} g6 7. fxg6 {, with a decisive attack.}) (4...
Nc6 5. Ne2 Nb4 {is popular, but I feel that delaying development that strongly
is too high a price to pay for getting the two bishops.}) 5. Kf1 $5 {White
defends g2 in order to prevent ...f7-f5.} (5. Nd2 f5 {offers Black comfortable
play.} 6. Qe2 (6. Qh5+ g6 7. Qe2 Nf6 8. f3 Nc6 9. d5 Nd4 10. Qe3 fxe4 11. fxe4
{Likavsky,T (2409)-Czebe,A (2520) Slovakia 2001 (1/2-1/2, 53)} Bc5 $19) (6. f3
{Aoshima,M (2280)-Furuya, M (1938) Tokyo 2018 (1-0, 66)} Qf6 7. Ne2 fxe4 8.
fxe4 Nh6 $11) 6... Nf6 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qe3 ({It is no surprise already that} 8. e5
{loses a pawn:} Nxd4 9. Qe3 Nh5 10. Qxd4 Bc5 11. Qc3 Qh4+ 12. Kd1 Ng3 $19 {
Trincardi,T (2235)-Karlsson,L (2375) Eksjo 1979 (0-1, 30)}) 8... fxe4 9. fxe4
O-O 10. Ngf3 {Prochnow,M (2250) -Ellers,H (2260) Germany 1997 (1/2-1/2, 30)}
Ng4 11. Qe2 Rxf3 12. Qxf3 Qh4+ 13. Qg3 (13. g3 Nxd4 $19) 13... Qxg3+ 14. hxg3
Nxd4 15. Rh4 Ne5 $19) (5. Bd2 {is examined in Line 24.}) 5... Be7 $1 {Black
has wasted a tempo, but so has White. Moreover, White will need to spend some
time to get castled artificially.} 6. Nc3 d6 7. Nf3 Nd7 ({Now or on the next
move,} 7... Nf6 {makes Black's position too rigid.} 8. g3 O-O 9. Kg2 Nbd7 10.
Qe2 c5 11. d5 $14 {So, W (2744)-Jobava,B (2713) Bergamo 2014 (1-0, 37)}) 8. g3
(8. Be3 {does not change much.} Bf6 {More about this setup in the next
commentary on the mainline.} 9. Qd2 Ne7 10. g4 {Mohammad,N (2380)-Gunnarsson,J
(2466) chess.com INT 2018 (1/2-1/2, 20)} c5 $1 11. Nb5 (11. d5 O-O 12. g5 Bxc3
13. Qxc3 Ng6 $15 {In view of possible pawn breaks on both wings (...b6-b5 or ..
.f7-f6), White's position is unstable.}) 11... O-O 12. Nxd6 cxd4 13. Nxd4 Qb8
14. Nxb7 Qxb7 {, followed by ...Rad8 and ...Nc5, with a strong initiative.})
8... Bf6 $1 {Black switches to a pseudo-Hyppopotamus setup. Usually he does
that with ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7, but with the pawn on g7 he can think of a later
...Bxc3 without weakening the dark squares.} 9. Kg2 Ne7 10. h4 ({Or if} 10. Re1
O-O 11. Be3 c5 12. d5 (12. Bc2 cxd4 13. Nxd4 a6 {leads to a Hedgehog that is
somewhat unstable for White, as the bishop is far away from g2.}) 12... Bxc3 {
Transposing to some sort of Nimzo-Indian is typical in this line.} ({Neutral
play is also possible:} 12... Ng6 13. Qd2 a6 14. Rad1 h6 15. h4 Re8 {, with
chances for both sides.}) 13. bxc3 h6 14. Qd2 Ng6 15. a4 Ba6 $11) 10... O-O (
10... c5 {is also possible.} 11. d5 Bxc3 12. bxc3 h6 13. Re1 O-O 14. a4 {
Rahman,M (2196)-Reefat, B (2417) Dhaka 2019 (1/2-1/2, 23)} Ng6 15. h5 Nge5 16.
Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Be2 Ba6 {, with comfortable play.}) 11. Bg5 (11. h5 c5 12. d5 {
Korchmar,V (2446)-Kunin,V (2533) Moscow 2020 (0-1, 51)} Bxc3 13. bxc3 h6 $11) (
11. Bd2 {over-defends c3 but leaves d4 undefended.} c5 12. d5 h6 13. h5 (13.
Qe2 Ng6 14. h5 Nge5 $11) 13... Bd4 $5 $11) 11... c5 12. d5 Bxc3 13. bxc3 h6 14.
Bf4 e5 15. Bc1 f5 $11 {Goganov,A (2564)-Alekseev,E (2616) Serpukhov 2018 (1/
2-1/2, 46)} *

