1. d4 e6 2. c4 b6 3. e4 Bb7 4. Bd3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 {This is the most natural and
popular answer.} Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 (6. Nxd2 {defends e4 but releases the potential
pressure along the d-file.} d6 $1 {Black does well changing plans. With the
knight on d2, the blockade on the dark squares should work fine.} (6... f5 {
allows} 7. Ngf3 $14 {, when Black has to take on e4 earlier than he would like
to.}) 7. Ne2 {Keeping the f-pawn's path free.} (7. Ngf3 Nd7 8. O-O e5 9. d5 a5
10. Bc2 Ne7 11. a3 O-O 12. b4 h6 13. Nb3 f5 $11 {Goryachkina,A (2452)-Paehtz,E
(2454) Riga 2017 (1/2-1/2, 35)}) 7... Ne7 8. O-O O-O 9. f4 Nd7 10. Nf3 e5 11.
Bc2 (11. fxe5 dxe5 12. d5 {Poghosyan,S (2273)-Kostenko,P (2457) Batumi 2015 
(1-0, 34)} a5 $11 {, with a reliable blockade.}) 11... c5 (11... exf4 12. Nxf4
c5 $11 {is simpler.}) 12. fxe5 dxe5 13. d5 Nc8 14. Ba4 Nd6 {White has more
space, but Black's blockade offers him good chances in the long run.} 15. Qd3
Qe7 16. Rae1 Rad8 17. Nc3 Nf6 18. Nb5 Nc8 19. Nh4 g6 20. Qf3 Ne8 21. g3 a6 22.
Na3 Ncd6 {Black's position is promising already. Sochacki,W (2302)-Sethuraman,
S (2623) Paris 2015 (0-1, 46)}) 6... f5 7. Nc3 Nf6 (7... fxe4 {offers White
the freer development:} 8. Bxe4 Bxe4 9. Nxe4 Nf6 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Nf3 Nc6 12.
O-O $14) 8. f3 (8. Qe2 {wastes too much time.} Qe7 $1 9. Nf3 (9. a3 Nc6 10. Nf3
fxe4 11. Nxe4 O-O-O $11 12. Nxf6 $6 Qxf6 13. Qe3 h6 14. O-O-O Rhf8 15. Rhf1 Na5
16. Be2 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Qf4 $17 {Sigurbjornsson,S (1996)-Gunnarsson,J (2460)
Reykjavik 2018 (0-1, 28)}) 9... fxe4 10. Nxe4 {Lysyj,I (2663)-Alekseev,E (2626)
Kolomna 2016 (1/2-1/2, 41)} Qb4+ 11. Nc3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Qxb2 13. O-O Nc6 14. Nb5
O-O $11) 8... Nc6 9. Nge2 {The most consistent.} (9. exf5 {offers White more
of a symbolic advantage.} Nxd4 10. Qe3 c5 11. Nge2 Nxe2 12. Qxe2 Qe7 (12... O-O
13. fxe6 Re8 14. O-O-O Rxe6 15. Qd2 $14) 13. fxe6 Qxe6 14. Qxe6+ dxe6 15. O-O-O
Rd8 16. Rhe1 Kf7 17. a3 Rd7 18. Kc2 {Williamson,D (2365)-Gnilka,T (2350) ICCF
email 2018 (1-0, 22)} a5 19. Re3 Bc6 20. Rde1 Re8 {, and Black should have no
special problems.}) 9... fxe4 10. fxe4 (10. Nxe4 Nxe4 {The simplest.} (10...
Qe7 11. O-O O-O 12. a3 a5 {Rakic,T (1971)-Gara,T (2367) Kragujevac 2015 (0-1,
27)}) 11. Bxe4 (11. fxe4 O-O {prevents White from castling short.} 12. O-O-O
Qe7 $11) 11... d5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Bc2 Qh4+ 14. g3 Qf6 15. O-O-O O-O-O $11)
10... O-O 11. O-O e5 {Black cannot delay this pawn break anymore.} 12. d5 (12.
dxe5 {is too simplistic.} Nxe5 13. Ng3 Qe7 (13... d6 14. h3 Bc8 15. Rf2 Be6 16.
b3 Nfd7 17. Rxf8+ {1/2-1/2 Sosonko,G (2585)-Ree,H (2500) Nijmegen 1983}) 14.
Nf5 Qc5+ 15. Kh1 Rae8 $15) 12... Ne7 13. Ng3 d6 {White has more space, but
Black's blockade on the dark squares is reliable.} 14. Nf5 (14. Nce2 Bc8 15. h3
Qe8 16. Kh2 Bd7 17. Qe3 Qg6 18. Nf5 Bxf5 19. exf5 Qh5 20. Kg1 Qh4 21. Rf2 b5 {
With strong counterplay. Jensen,H (2023)-Hansen,L (2207) Esbjerg 2019 (0-1, 47)
}) 14... Nxf5 15. exf5 c6 16. dxc6 Bxc6 17. Rad1 Qc7 18. Be2 Rad8 19. Qe3 Rfe8
20. b3 a6 21. Bf3 b5 $132 {With active play for Black. Riazantsev,A (2650)
-Alekseev,E (2616) Riadh 2017 (0-1, 31)} *

